  "prompt": "What is a microstrip antenna?",
  "response": "A microstrip antenna, also known as a patch antenna, is a type of radio antenna that can be mounted on a flat surface. It consists of a flat rectangular sheet or \"patch\" of metal, mounted over a larger sheet of metal called a ground plane. These two metal sheets together form a resonant piece of microstrip transmission line with a length around one-half wavelength of the radio waves used. The two metal sheets are sandwiched between two layers of dielectric material, typically a printed circuit board substrate, to form a compact structure.\n\nMicrostrip antennas are popular in applications where a low-profile, conformal antenna is required, such as in aircraft, missiles, and satellite communications. They are also commonly used in wireless communication devices like mobile phones, GPS receivers, and Wi-Fi devices due to their low cost and ease of manufacture. However, they have a relatively narrow bandwidth and low gain compared to other types of antennas.",
